{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10285,"record_hash":"sha256:a7c5be6352fd04a7642e58c02e61057a7307c21174452dccac598cdb2daa7b8e","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:57:16.476Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 68dd74\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1355\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Handoff Design\n\nThis note sketches the handoff feature that sits above the `but-agentlog`\nprimitives. It is intentionally not an implementation contract yet.\n\n## Goal\n\nLet a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\nanother machine, agent, or provider session.\n\nThe target experience:\n\n1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n5. the agent uses GitButler commands to discover and read relevant prior session\n   context\n6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n\nThis is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n\n## Current Building Blocks\n\nThe primitive layer can already provide the facts a handoff flow needs:\n\n- durable project-scoped sessions\n- capture turns within sessions\n- ordered transcript records within each turn\n- environment observations for each turn\n- GitMeta sync of the stored data\n- verified lookup of sessions related to a branch, review, or change\n- bounded hydration of related turn windows\n\nThat is enough to design an agent-facing workflow without adding product-shaped\nstate to `but-agentlog`.\n\n## Current Data Feasibility Check\n\nLooking at the live GitMeta database for the `agentlog-turn-storage` branch on\n2026-05-20, the proposed tools are realistic, but the data shape confirms that\nthey need to be bounded and metadata-heavy.\n\nObserved data:\n\n- 14 sessions related to the branch\n- 29 related turns\n- 7,357 stored transcript records\n- the largest main session has 16 turns and 6,037 records\n- the initial backfill turn in that session has 5,371 records\n- hydrating the largest session locally is fast enough for now, roughly 217ms\n- returning that session as full timeline\n[TRUNCATED]\nbut contain 5,371 captured records.\n- Current `find_related_sessions` returns sessions in key order, not recency\n  order. For catch-up, related sessions should be sorted by latest activity.\n- Current timeline hydration can read full records internally when convenient,\n  but the timeline command should not return full records. Full timeline output\n  is hundreds of times larger than the outline an agent needs for orientation.\n- Naive latest-user previews can surface internal provider events such as\n  subagent notifications. Those records should remain available in `records`,\n  but `sessions` and `timeline` previews should either label or skip them.\n- Observed branch/review/change targets show relation evidence, not ownership.\n  A branch can be observed by background review or sidecar work.\n\nThis means the minimal tools are feasible without a storage rewrite, but the\nread layer should be careful: sort by recency, expose match evidence, keep\ntimeline light, and page records by turn-local position.\n\n### Storage Decision\n\nDo not add persisted lightweight timeline data yet.\n\nThe current storage is good enough for the first handoff tools:\n\n- `TurnSummary` gives ordered turns and capture metadata.\n- `TurnDetail.records` gives authoritative per-turn render order.\n- the session transcript list gives full records by hash.\n- environment snapshots give observed branch/review/change evidence.\n\nThe important distinction is storage shape versus command output. It is fine for\nthe read layer to scan or hydrate existing records internally, as long as the\nagent-facing `timeline` response remains compact. The transcript itself should\nbe returned only by `records`, and `records` should be bounded by default.\n\nRevisit storage only if real usage shows a concrete bottleneck, such as very\nlarge sessions making repeated timeline reads too slow, or if providers expose\nreliable parent/root session fields that would let us store session lineage\nwithout guessing.\n\n## Design Bias\n\nThe agent should get tools, not a generated handoff essay.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:57:16.476Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}